Certainly! Below is the modified code with the new catch block added to handle the "HttpServerErrorException$InternalServer Error: 500 Internal Server Error" exception:

```java
try {
    // existing code
} catch (HttpClientErrorException e) {
    e.printStackTrace();
    LOGGER.error("Error triggering job", e.getMessage());
    FileMetadata metadata = kafkaConsumer.logMetadata(collector, fileType, e);
    kafkaInputProducer.sendFailureMessage(collector, fileType, e);
    kafkaConsumer.writeLogToFile(metadata, destinationFolderPath);
} catch (HttpServerErrorException.InternalServerError e) {
    LOGGER.error("Internal Server Error: 500", e.getMessage());
    // Handle specific actions for this type of exception
}
```

In the modified code, I've added a new catch block specifically for handling the `HttpServerErrorException.InternalServerError` exception. This catch block will handle the exception and log an error message. Additionally, you can perform specific actions related to handling this type of exception within the catch block.